{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502338"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:42:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:42:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1847"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1847"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.52,0.31,0.05,0.08,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1847"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112748"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1847"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1847"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94782"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"527"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4046"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1507"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1518"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40759"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46353"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112748","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112748"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old man is admitted with a 12 hour history of anorexia and constant lower right-sided abdominal pain radiating into his groin. He looks unwell, with a blood pressure of 120/70 mmHg, heart rate of 90/min and temperature of 37.4C. His abdomen is soft, apart from some tenderness to deep palpation in the right iliac fossa and suprapubic region. Urinalysis shows a trace of blood. A CT scan is performed (image 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ureteric colic","Appendicitis","Diverticulitis","Psoas abscess","Crohn\u0027s disease"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA distended and thickened appendix is visible, tipping into the pelvic brim (Image 1 and 2). Its position in close proximity to the bladder explains the presence of microscopic haematuria from local irritation. Inflammation of a pelvic appendix can also lead to leukocytes being detected in the urine, for the same reason. This is a case of \u003Cstrong\u003Eappendicitis\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst\u003Cstrong\u003E renal stones\u003C/strong\u003E are classically associated with pain radiating into the groin, as is the case here, suprapubic tenderness on abdominal examination is less likely. Furthermore, CT KUB (non-contrast) is likely to demonstrate the presence of an obstructing stone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiverticulitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a disease seen more commonly in older patient groups and most often presents with left-sided abdominal pain. Findings on CT are generally consistent with acute colonic inflammation and include thickening and enhancement of the bowel wall, as well as fat stranding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsoas abscess\u003C/strong\u003E can be a cause of right lower quadrant abdominal pain, however it has a far lower incidence than appendicitis and thus, is less likely in this case. Patients also tend to have a higher grade fever, and an immunosuppressed state is a significant risk factor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECrohn\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E, particularly an acute flare, can sometimes be difficult to distinguish from appendicitis. Accurate history-taking can be helpful, as it will often reveal altered bowel habit (diarrhoea with or without blood) and abdominal cramping/bloating over an extended period of time. Examination will sometimes reveal a mass in the right lower quadrant. The terminal ileum and caecum are the most commonly involved regions and thus, CT scan will often demonstrate bowel wall thickening, tissue congestion and oedema, as well as mesenteric fat stranding.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In cases of suspected appendicitis, where there is diagnostic doubt, CT imaging is quite appropriate."],"references":["Dixon F, Singh A. Acute appendicitis. Surgery (Oxford). 2020 Jun;38(6):310-317. Available at: https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Frances-Dixon-2/publication/341675237_Acute_appendicitis/links/617aa4220be8ec17a93cfa55/Acute-appendicitis.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94782"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1847"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15050"},{"type":"media","id":"15051"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21463"},{"type":"media","id":"21464"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15050","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15050"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1a7ad833-e4dc-4f2c-b6d8-a0654a88af27.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1a7ad833-e4dc-4f2c-b6d8-a0654a88af27.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":599}},{"type":"media","id":"15051","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15051"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5bee7471-cb2e-4fba-b8cb-e1a48059ea22.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5bee7471-cb2e-4fba-b8cb-e1a48059ea22.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":800}},{"type":"media","id":"21463","links":{"self":"https://app.em